{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17627206","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17627206"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:46:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:46:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17106"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17106","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17106"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.57,0.06,0.12,0.12,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9796"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77358"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9796","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9796"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17106"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62865"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5058"},{"type":"tags","id":"5068"},{"type":"tags","id":"7178"},{"type":"tags","id":"9861"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22974"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23154"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77358","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77358"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDobutamine is commonly used in the intensive care setting to support cardiac function.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of dobutamine?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Beta-1 adrenergic receptor agonism","Muscarinic receptor antagonism","Beta-2 adrenergic receptor agonism","Dopamine receptor agonism","Alpha-1 adrenergic receptor agonism"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeta-1 adrenergic receptor agonism\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary mechanism of action of dobutamine. This results in increased cardiac contractility (positive inotropic effect) and heart rate (positive chronotropic effect), leading to improved cardiac output.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Ealpha-1 adrenergic receptor agonism\u003C/strong\u003E does occur in the peripheral vasculature, this is not its primary mechanism for improving cardiac output. Alpha-1 agonism is largely balanced by beta-2 effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeta-2 adrenergic receptor agonism\u003C/strong\u003E in the peripheral vasculature does occur, opposing the alpha-1 agonism described above. Again, these are not the primary mechanisms that describe why dobutamine is used to improve cardiac output. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDopamine receptor agonism\u003C/strong\u003E is not a significant mechanism of dobutamine, unlike its structural analogue dopamine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMuscarinic receptor antagonism\u003C/strong\u003E is not part of dobutamine\u0027s pharmacological profile.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe balanced beta-2 and alpha-1 effects of dobutamine result in mild vasodilation, making it particularly useful in treating acute heart failure where increased cardiac output is needed. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dobutamine is a synthetic catecholamine that primarily stimulates beta-1 adrenergic receptors to increase cardiac contractility.","Dobutamine has minimal effects on peripheral vascular resistance due to fairly balanced beta-2 and alpha-1 receptor activity.","The main clinical use of dobutamine is in acute heart failure where inotropy is required to improve cardiac output."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62865"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17106"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62865","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62865"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T18:00:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T18:00:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9796"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77358"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","p